\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
FV_{n}=\ensuremath{V\text{\cdot}(1+R)^{n}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $FV_{n}$
\end_inset

 is future value after 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 years.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So after, say, 1 year, the initial investment grows to 
\begin_inset Formula $V\cdot(1+R)$
\end_inset

, after 2 years 
\begin_inset Formula $V\cdot(1+R)(1+R)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Example
\series default
: Consider putting $1000 in an interest checking account that pays a simple
 annual percentage rate of 3%.
 The future value after n = 1, 5 and 10 years is, respectively, 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $FV_{1}$
\end_inset

= $1000 · (1.03) 1 = $1030, 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $FV_{5}$
\end_inset

= $1000 · (1.03) 5 = $1159.27, 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $FV_{10}$
\end_inset

= $1000 · (1.03) 10 = $1343.92.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
FV function is a relationship between four variables 
\begin_inset Formula $FV_{n}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

.
 Given three variables, you can solve for the fourth:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Present Value
\series default

\begin_inset Formula 
\[
V=\frac{FV_{n}}{(1+R)^{n}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Compound annual return
\series default
 - average annual interest rate that you get every year that compounds such
 that the investment grows to the future value
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
R=\left(\frac{FV_{n}}{V}\right)^{\frac{1}{n}}-1
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Investment horizon
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
n=\frac{ln\left(\frac{FV_{n}}{V}\right)}{ln(1+R)}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Investment horizon answers a question 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

how long does it take the money to double
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 Related to the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

rule of 70
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
2 & = & V(1+R)^{n}\\
\ln2 & = & n\ln(1+R)\\
n & = & \frac{\ln(2)}{\ln(1+R)}\approx\frac{0.7}{R}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Ex.: If 
\begin_inset Formula $R=0.01$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $n=\frac{0.7}{0.01}=70$
\end_inset

 years for the money to double.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Compounding can occur 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 times per year
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
FV_{n}^{m}=\ensuremath{V\cdot(1+\frac{R}{m})^{m\cdot n}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{R}{m}=\text{periodic interest rate}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Continuous compounding
