\begin_layout Standard
Because we can have compounding periods different from a year, there's a
 concept of 
\series bold
Effective Annual Rate
\series default
.
 For example, we effectively have a higher interest rate when we compoud
 daily than annually, like in the above example.
 So for the above example the effective annual rate for daily compounding
 frequency is 10.5%.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Effective Annual Rate
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Annual rate 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{A}$
\end_inset

 that equates 
\begin_inset Formula $FV_{n}^{m}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $FV_{n}$
\end_inset

 i.e.
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
V\cdot\left(1+\frac{R}{m}\right)^{m\cdot n} & = & V\cdot(1+R_{A})^{n}\\
(1+\frac{R}{m})^{m} & = & 1+R_{A}\\
\mathbf{R_{A}} & \mathbf{=} & \mathbf{\left(1+\frac{R}{m}\right)^{m}-1}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

