\begin_layout Paragraph
Simple Returns
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Buy stock, hold it for a period of time and sell, want to know whta the
 return on that will be.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Holding Period Return
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The idea is that we have a price 0, 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{0}$
\end_inset

, of some asset.
 At some 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 in the future we're going to sell the asset at 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{t}$
\end_inset

.
 
\series bold
Holding Period Return:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\underset{\text{over holding period}}{\%\Delta P}=\frac{P_{t}-P_{0}}{P_{0}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Holding periods are often standardized to 1 month, they could be 2.34 days.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $P_{t}$
\end_inset

 - price at the end of month t on an asset that pays no dividends
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $P_{t-1}$
\end_inset

- price at the end of month 
\begin_inset Formula $t-1$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Net return over month t:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
R_{t}=\frac{P_{t}-P_{t-1}}{P_{t-1}}=\%\Delta P_{t}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Gross return over month t:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
1+R_{t}=\frac{P_{t}}{P_{t-1}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
can think of this as: if we have $1, invested at 
\begin_inset Formula $t-1$
\end_inset

, how much does that dollar grow after 1 month.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Example
\series default
: One month investment in Microsoft stock.
 Buy stock at end of month 
\begin_inset Formula $t-1$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{t}-1=\$85$
\end_inset

 and sell stock at end of next month for 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{t}=\$90$
\end_inset

.
 Assuming that Microsoft does not pay a dividend between months 
\begin_inset Formula $t-1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

, the one-month simple net and gross returns are:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
R_{t} & = & \frac{90-85}{85}=\frac{90}{85}-1=1.0588-1\\
 & = & 0.588
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
1+R_{t}=1.0588
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The one month investment in Microsoft yielded a 5.88% per month return.
 (unusual, maybe in the 90s)
\end_layout

