\begin_layout Subsubsection
Continuously Compounded Returns
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Simple returns are based on the percentage change in price.
 One of their features is that if we look at the relationship between single-per
iod returns and multi-period returns, it was multiplicative.
 So one year return was e.g.
 a geometric average of one month returns.
 From the point of view of modeling, it's better if things are additive.
 Continuously compounded returns give us this property.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $r_{t}$
\end_inset

- Continuously Compounded Return, continuously compounded growth rate of
 prices between two periods.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Computational Trick
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When you see macro data, like GDP plotted over time, it's often a logarithm
 instead of the price.
 That's done, because the slope of the logarithm represents the growth rate
 from one period to the next.
 So the elasticity in this case would be the same as the continuously compounded
 growth rate between two time periods.
 Same for prices, slope of the log-price graph would be the continuously
 compounded return between two time periods.
\end_layout

